docs.abstract: An Apple Watch or a Garmin can draw incorrect conclusions about your health, but the broad trends may be more valuable than the numbers.
docs.snippet: An Apple Watch or a Garmin can draw incorrect conclusions about your health, but the broad trends may be more valuable than the numbers.
docs.lead_paragraph: Smartwatches from tech companies like Apple and Garmin make it easy to see a number that could reflect how old you are more accurately than your age: the VO2max, the maximum amount of oxygen that your body can use during intense exercise.

headline.main: What Good Are Wearable Computers if the Data Is Wrong?
headline.print_headline: Fitness Data on Your Smartwatch May Be Wrong, and Yet Very Right

docs.abstract: The Wall Street giant’s latest financial results show how its push into consumer banking remains a drag on its overall business.

docs.lead_paragraph: Bank of America reported on Tuesday that deposits fell less than analysts had expected last quarter, and BNY Mellon reported a slight increase in deposits, pushing their shares up in premarket trading as investors see more evidence that the country’s biggest lenders grew stronger after Silicon Valley Bank’s demise last month.

headline.main: Goldman Sachs Falters Amid Strong Earnings From Big Banks
